liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian Energy Regulator (AER) has launched court proceedings two subsidiaries of AGL Energy for allegedly failing to provide back up electricity services, breaching the National Electricity Rules. The AER alleges the subsidiaries — AGL Macquarie and AGL Loy Yang — made offers to the Australian Energy Market Operator (AEMO) and were paid to be on standby to provide contingency "frequency control ancillary services" (FCAS) in response to disturbances. The AER says both subsidiaries admitted to not complying with dispatch instructions given to them by AEMO regarding their FCAS offers, and failed to ensure their relevant generating units were able to comply with them. "Under the National Electricity Rules, electricity generators can offer to be on standby to  provide market ancillary services to stabilise network frequency when there is a power  system disturbance," the AER said. "Contingency FCAS is a type of market ancillary service and is essential  to keeping the lights on following a frequency disturbance in the power system." The AER alleges AGL Macquarie failed to comply with the instructions between September 2018 and August 2020 at its Bayswater power station, and between December 2019 and May 2020 at AGL's Loy Yang A power station. Both subsidiaries have cooperated with the AER, and the regulator says the parties intend to make joint submissions to the Federal Court.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: AGL Energy entities charged by regulator for breaching National Electricity Rules

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you missed this news yesterday, health insurer Medibank is facing a shareholder class action in the Supreme Court of Victoria over its data breach last year. Law firm Phi Finney McDonald is representing shareholders, who are seeking compensation after 9.7 million Medibank customers had their personal information stolen during last year's hack. In a statement yesterday, the firm noted Medibank's share price plummeted more than 18% while it was placed in a trading halt between October 19 and October 26. My colleague Gareth Hutchens covered this in yesterday's blog, which you can conveniently find here .
